Binary/CLI entry point (`cargo run --bin build_nvim`) that compiles `dict.steno` into the two artifacts consumed by the Neovim steno plugin: `out/vim-snippets.json` (stroke → keyset token, fed to Plover as a plain lookup table) and `out/snippets.json` (token → LSP snippet body with tabstops, expanded client-side by the nvim plugin). The split exists so Plover never needs to know about snippet expansion — it just emits a token string.

All real logic (parsing, expansion, snippet building, JSON serialization) lives in the `steno` lib crate (`parse_source`, `expand_dict`, `build_snippets`, `to_json`, `OrderedMap`); this file is orchestration only. `run()` pipeline: read `dict.steno` from workspace root → `parse_source` → `expand_dict(&entries, None)` → `build_snippets` → `guard` collisions → write both JSON files via `write_json`. If `build.collisions` is non-empty, `guard` aborts with an error message listing every unique colliding keyset *before* `out_dir` is created or anything is written — a build with collisions leaves `out/` untouched (doesn't even clear stale files from a previous run).

`root()` resolves the workspace root as `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/../..`, i.e. it hardcodes this binary's crate being two directories below the workspace root containing `dict.steno` — moving `steno` crate would break this. `write_json` canonicalizes `out_dir` before writing (so printed paths are absolute) and returns the byte length written, used by `run()` to print a combined total.

Errors are all stringly-typed (`Result<_, String>`) and funneled to `fail()`, which prints to stderr and returns `ExitCode::FAILURE`; `main` never panics on expected failure paths. `out_line` and stderr writes swallow their own I/O errors (`let _ =`) since there's no fallback reporting channel if stdout/stderr itself fails.